1083530910857752576.text: Medicine doesn't give two fucking shits about how women react to meds, how our reactions may be different to men, how they may be similar. My legitimate concerns were dismissed outright despite being a listed side effect because "that only happens to men". It clearly doesn't.

1083530908764762114.text: Told me that these reactions were unusual. Guess what? All the studies I found on my medication were done on men. Lo and behold, I asked around and I'm not the only woman to experience these issues on this medication.

1083530906076213248.text: And it's so indicative of women's health and experience with medication being dismissed. Recently one of my most helpful doctors dismissed my assertions that one of my medications was negatively impacting my libido and sexual function. Told me "only men experience these issues".

1083530902863400960.text: My doctors dismissed my concerns and told me it was fine. Patient experience and reports changed my mind. Why aren't these experiences getting reported? Why do doctors dismiss them as rare one off's when they aren't.

1083530901328355328.text: Refer to @Asher_Wolf tweets about the experience of having an IUD as an hEDS patient and how absolutely terribly that went. It's horrifying.

1083530899352768512.text: Few were positive. But overwhelmingly the answers were alarming and negative. IUDs wandering, expelling themselves, causing period irregulaties, causing extreme upticks in pain and muscle issues in EDS patients. I decided against it.

1083530897872175107.text: When you are a clotting risk, you can't have estrogen. I was recommended an IUD. I was reluctant so I did my research and found some evidence to suggest that IUDs are contraindicated for EDS patients. I took to Facebook support groups for both conditions to ask their experiences.

1083530896299286528.text: Last year I was diagnosed with a little known condition called May-Thurners Compression Syndrome. It puts me at risk of blood clots. I was also diagnosed as more likely than not, of having a genetic connective tissue disorder, Hypermobile Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome.

1083530894667788289.text: The problem would absolutely be a lack of knowledge, or acknowledgement, on the medical side. Doctors don't listen to women. Or when they do, they outright ignore, dismiss, or refute our claims and experiences.

1083530892377653248.text: The question should be "what are doctors doing wrong here and how can we fix that". Because if women are communicating in large numbers that they are desperate enough to remove their own IUD at home because of side effects, the problem isn't a lack of patient knowledge.

1056157450003341314.text: All of these doctors have, bit by bit, helped to repair the damage that the #DoctorsAreDickheads ones have done. If you're a doctor caring for us complex folk - take note. Kindness, empathy, understanding, and honesty goes a long way. It really does.

1056157447847473153.text: She's given me exercises, new treatment options, recommendations for specific exercise classes for hypermobile people. She sees me at my worst, every two weeks, and is always kind. She gets it. I don't know where I'd be without her.

1056157444810846209.text: And of course, there's my physiotherapist. Who I've seen every two weeks for the last four years. Who listens, who encouraged me to get more answers, who puts me back together week in week out and is constantly trying to find new ways to help me.

1056157442361323520.text: He's actively working to research POTS and dysautonomia and build a team of doctors to help complex cases. Because he's mad that it's taking years from the lives of young women because doctors don't know how to diagnose it. He believes me, and has made a WORLD OF DIFFERENCE.

1056157440239054848.text: My cardiologist, who upon hearing me say that I'd almost accepted that my symptoms were all in my head because I'd been dismissed so often said "rarely, when patients seek me out and get to this appointment, do we find it's all in their head."

1056157437776949248.text: But the biggest thing? She looked at me and said "I believe that your pain is real, and I will do what I can to help you". Kind, compassionate, honest. She's a #DoctorIRespect.

1019098582173904896.text: So why go through the trouble of setting permissions on ~200 documents only to cancel #MyHealthRecord? Because I don't trust this system. I don't trust that my account wont just get randomly opened up at some point again in the future leaving all my info accessible.

1019098580588490752.text: This system is seriously lacking, and to just dump this quantity of data into your #MyHealthRecord without giving you an easy way to bulk manage permissions is frankly insane practice. Most people wont have the inclination to go through and set permissions the way I did.

1019098578873036801.text: For documents within the last two years, this was a 6 click process to 'effectively remove' the document from your record. Anything older than two years, you had to reset the date picker each time you removed one, so it was a 10 click process. Absolute UX nightmare.

1019098577388179456.text: There were ~200 documents in there, all from Medicare, including prescriptions and hospital discharge notes. There's no way to bulk opt-out of their open security preferences so you have to manually revoke access for every single document individually.
